post_text:
Dear Mount Baker Community,

We are operating on a remote instructional model with limited onsite instruction and programs. Use of District facilities at this time is limited to our personnel, approved student groups, and approved contractors.

To practice utmost caution, at this time use of the facilities by outside entities is prohibited. No Facility Use Agreements should be executed until further notice.

post_text:
William Stich, a MBHS student, is going to be returning to Mount Baker in the fall, four days before senior year begins. William is currently on a 48 state tour with his Pandemic Quilt; he is 20 states into the 48 state tour - visit www.pandemicquilt.com for photos.

Here are some photos of William meeting the distinguished head of the COVID-19 and Swine Flu division of the CDC, as well as from the Statue of Liberty and Freedom Tower 9/11. One of his quilts was dedicated at the CDC and will hang in the Emergency Operation room at the CDC in Atlanta. William was presented with Challenge Coins, which are extremely hard to receive, and he even got one from the lead doctor (she is the one that testifies at Congress, etc.). This is truly a honor.

Congratulations William!!!

Please join me in appreciation of our certificated staff. They are Baker Strong, Teacher Strong, and Character Strong! You have all worked miracles and transformed learning in a matter of weeks. We are grateful for our community partners, MAD HOPE and NAMI Whatcom, whom are partnering to offer a Community Conversation around Social Media and Youth Mental Wellness.
This community conversation, featuring Dr. David Sattler of WWU’s Psychology Department and partners from DVSAS (domestic violence prevention) and NW ESD 189 (student assistance) is an upcoming, easily accessible and timely conversation meant to inform the participant around safety and how to have positive experiences as social media users.

post_text: Mt. Baker Plant Sale update #2 🌷🌼🍅🥬🥒🌶
shared_text:
Tamara Whitcomb‎Mt. Baker Plant Sale
April 12 at 6:30 PM ·

Mt. Baker Plant Sale - Update #2 - Plant Sale Prices

Happy Easter Everyone! This is what everyone has been waiting for...the initial Plant Sale variety and price list. Both plants and prices are subject to change as I first have to keep everything alive for the next month. : ) Although I appreciate your enthusiasm, I will not be taking pre-orders for our plants. Mt. Baker Plant Sale - April 5th Update
“Think Spring” everyone! The Mt. Baker plants are continuing to grow and fill out their containers in the greenhouse this week and several are finally getting their blooms. I appreciate everyone’s support and patience as I work out the details for our annual plant sale scheduled to start on Wednesday, May 6th at 9 am. More details will be made available in the coming weeks, so please continue to be patient. Also...although I truly appreciate everyone volunteering to help, now is the time to stay safe and comfortable at home and get your containers, landscape beds and gardens ready for the plants you wish to purchase. Plants from our greenhouse will be made available to all staff and community members on the same day (no pre-orders please), but I encourage you to check out the pictures I took this morning and start keeping a list at home of what you would like. Plant prices will also be made available next week. Many thanks to such a supportive community and stay tuned for upcoming information on our plant sale. ~Tamara Whitcomb

post_text: I am so appreciative of my Mount Baker Community and so proud and thankful for every Mount Baker School District staff member. I have been in education for 36 years and have been an administrator for 23 years. Never have I been challenged with the circumstances that we are navigating now. Everyone is all in when it comes to serving students. Teachers and staff are mobilizing remotely to do amazing things to ensure students get the best learning possible during this time. I have never been so proud! This speaks to the "Power of Baker" and the compassion and commitment throughout our community. Joining this community as a citizen and the Superintendent of Mount Baker School District is the best decision I have ever made. Go Baker!!

The power of Baker:
-I am so grateful to all community members. We come together in tough times
-I am so grateful for my administrative team for working with me to ensure we support all students and families. This work is ongoing and changes by the hour
-Our Child Nutrition and Transportation teams are awesome. They are getting thousands of meals out per week
-We are working on staff communications and learning supports for students. Our instructional staff are miracle workers
-Our custodians and maintenance staff are working hard everyday
-We know how important staff relationships are for students. Staff and coaches will be reaching out soon
-We are committed to meeting the academic, social, emotional, and physical needs of all students given all the current and future challenges

A big thank you to all staff at all levels for putting kids first! Thank you parents and community members. Together, we will make good things happen. Go Baker!!

With gratitude,

Mary Sewright

Mount Baker School District is starting our Reverse the Baker Bus meal deliveries. The plan is as follows:

🔘Small buses will be doing the food deliveries from 10:00am - 12:00pm, on Tuesdays and Fridays.

🔘These buses will be stopping at established Elementary morning routes

🔘Please listen for the bus to honk/look for the bus - we are not sure exactly what time it will be at each stop.

🔘Three (3) days worth of breakfast and lunch will be provided with each delivery.

🔘We ask that children be present to receive their meals.

🔘This service is free and available to children 0-18 years of age, regardless of their status for free lunch enrollment in the District.

We hope that this helps in some small way to get through the COVID-19 situation we are all experiencing.

Todd Rightmire shared a post to the group: Mt. Baker FFA.
March 13 at 3:18 PM ·

Washington FFA Association
March 13 at 2:14 PM ·

WA FFA Announcement on COVID-19

Given the Governor's announcement today closing ALL state schools and gatherings more than 250 people statewide until a minimum of April 24th,

Washington FFA is POSTPONING ALL Spring CDEs at this time.

The CDEs/LDEs that were under consideration for electronic options are also postponed.

We will NOT be holding any statewide FFA events during the school closure period from March 13–April 24, 2020.

The WA FFA Board of Directors will be meeting virtually next week to evaluate the status of state convention (which is scheduled outside of the currently mandated closure period), constitutionally mandated delegate business, as well as qualifiers to go forward to National Convention. More information will be coming immediately following that board meeting.

The safety and health of our FFA family is paramount to WA FFA and we are working diligently to come up with contingency plans during this unprecedented time.

Mount Baker FFA won the Southwest Washington Forestry Career Development Event on Saturday, Feb. 29th at Toutle Lake High School. Jed Grimes was the high-scoring individual at the contest, winning 1st by more than 45 points. Colby Wagar was 3rd place, Lily Pike was 5th place, Thayer Brown was 6th place, and Jonah Hickey was 15th. There were 11 teams and 45 students competing in tree identification, tool identification, map reading, general knowledge, team cruising, compass course, disease and pest identification, and chainsaw parts identification/troubleshooting.

Congrats!!!

post_text:
The Mt. Baker FFA Booster Club Auction & Dinner is coming up!

When: March 7th @ 5:00 pm - 9:30 pm
Location: Deming Log Show

There will be a chicken/beef dinner, live auction, silent auction, and bucket raffle. Tickets are $20, and available from Todd Rightmire at MBHS. Contact (360) 617-4570 or email todd@mtbaker.wednet.edu. We recommend you purchase tickets prior to the event.

Auction items will be posted on our FFA website and on our Mt. Baker FFA Booster Club Facebook page starting next week. Last year, there were over 245 auction items!

Money from this auction goes towards sending 30+ students to State FFA Convention, supports our rotation animal program, purchasing some barn and fair supplies, financial support for exhibitors at fairs, stipend for student meals to different overnight activities, sending students to National FFA Convention, and sending up to two students to the Washington DC Leadership Conference.

post_text:
Join us tonight - Thursday, Jan. 23rd - at Pint Night to help raise money for our amazing group of young athletes in the Baker 542 Ride team!

Baker 542 Ride is the Special Olympics Ski and Snowboard team for the Whatcom County area, training at Mt. Baker.

The mission of the Special Olympics is to provide sports training and athletic competition in a variety of Olympic-type sports for children and adults with intellectual disabilities, giving them continuing opportunities to develop physical fitness, demonstrate courage, experience joy and participate in the sharing of gifts, skills, and friendship with their families, other Special Olympic athletes and the community.

post_text:
January is School Board Recognition Month!

The Mount Baker School District would like to thank our amazing School Board members for their dedication to our schools, students, and community.

Regular meetings are held at 6:00 PM on the second Thursday and 8:30 AM on the fourth Thursday in the District Office, unless otherwise noted on the School Board calendar. Meetings are open to the public; the public is invited and encouraged to attend Board meetings. Minutes of every School Board Meeting are posted on our website.

Learn more about the Mount Baker School Board at https://www.mtbaker.wednet.edu/schoolboard

post_text:
We hope everyone was able to avoid major issues and remained safe during this January snow storm!
The Mount Baker School District has determined the following make-up days for the January 13-17 late start and closure:

• January 14 – make up on May 1
• January 15 – make up on June 12
• January 16 – make up on June 15
• January 17 – make up on June 16
• June 10 & 11 will now be full days, and we will determine if June 15 & 16 can be early release days.

Note: these dates are subject to change if the District closes again due to inclement weather.

The girls placed 8th as a team and send Kali Cook (11th), Juliette Haggith (12th), and Zetta Schmidt (26th) to the state meet next Saturday in Pasco.

The boys placed 7th as a team and send Nico Johnson (6th), and Braedan Hart (22nd) to state.

All runners are making return trips to state. Juliette is making her 4th consecutive trip to state. Kali is a 3 time state runner. Zetta, Nico, and Braedan are all returning for a second year in a row.

Nice job to all the runners this year!

shared_text:
Mount Baker School District added 9 new photos — in Leavenworth, Washington.
October 17, 2019 at 3:20 PM · Leavenworth, WA ·

#ThrowbackThursday to the Mount Baker Mountaineer Band performing in the Leavenworth Parade on September 28, 2019

Doug Sutton, the Mount Baker Jr/Sr High School band teacher, said of the trip: "It was raining during our pre-parade waiting time, but the kids used their ponchos which kept them and their uniforms dry. Our uniform managers worked hard to help their band-mates with uniform problems. The band played and marched better than they had during rehearsal, and they earned 2nd place in the 2A division of the parade! The students enjoyed some time to wander the Bavarian-themed town; many had bratwurst and sauerkraut. The students were a joy to be around from start to finish."

Mount Baker Family Services is reaching out to our community groups to donate Thanksgiving dinner baskets to families.

In the past, we've had churches, book groups, 4-H groups, and local companies support families by providing a full Thanksgiving meal. If you're part of a group that might be interested in providing a meal for one or more families, please contact Kate Davies @ (360) 617-4303 or kdavies@mtbaker.wednet.edu
